			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: 'splain some stuff to me, please!<a name="40153"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 16 04 1:10 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">1) True or False: There are several different types of play styles for bards - singing bard, tanking bard, buff bard. 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well in the early parts of the game you tend to be a tanking bard through necessity. Mid levels will expand your singing and buffing abilities and higher levels is going to refine your singing twists. 
<br />
Now ... IMO bards need to be all of these and more otherwise your just a 'gimp' tank or a 'gimp' buffer or a 'gimp' singer. What gives us our spotlight and shines as our class ability is the fact that we are ALL of these at the same time. 
<br />
You find a balance of buffs songs your melee or range actions that is best appropriate for the group / situation. AND you fill all of those roles to the best of your ability... this is what makes you a Bard... not that you can fill those roles but that you Will fill them all.
<br />
I had a cleric once tell me that you can't be a really uber bard unless you can twist more than 6 songs like this bard in her group was doing. I laughed at her it iss mathematically impossible to twist more than 6 of our songs continuously.. there's no practical application to even try. I told her then she didn't understand what a bard was nor what their roles in a raid or group was then if she thought that was the qualifying agent of a truly good bard. </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
